defaultWritten evidence submitted by defaultDr defaultCarrie Dunndefault [WAS0001]default&#xa0;defaultProfiledefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultAbout this defaultpaperdefault&#xa0;defaultThis briefing paper argues that women and girls need to feel that sport is open to them as spectators and participants – both equally important - rather than seeing it as a male-dominated field, which is still the case. I highlight some of the key a
defaultspects of female sports fandom, and suggest that despite the growing numbers of women involved in sport, it is still institutionally sexist, creating problems for those who object to covert and overt sexism.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe paper 
defaultfocuses on my completed research proj
defaultect into 
defaultthe experience of female fans of men's professional football in England, and based on a questionnaire completed by 100 respondents of varying demographic followed by 27 in-depth interviews. I also interviewed club directors and representatives of 
defaultthe FA and Football League to add context to my findings.
default&#xa0;
defaultI am currently working on a research project looking at the significance of elite sporting role models to young participants, focusing on football and cricket.
