default1)default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe role of the familydefault&#xa0;
defaultF
defaultemale fans tend to be introduced to football by family members, who encourage their spectatorship, often as part of a familial tradition. This mostly occurs in childhood. I suggest that if girls are put off football or they are told that it is “for boys”, 
defaultthey accept and do not question this, and remain outside football for the rest of their lives. Occasionally women begin watching football in adulthood, but my findings indicate that this is not particularly common, giving the lie to the stereotype that adu
defaultlt women go to football only to keep their husband or boyfriend company.
default&#xa0;
defaultRespondents indicated that strong personal influences played a large role in initiating them into football support, with a particular individual (a family member, a friend or colleag
defaultue) being identified as a significant initiator in 91% of questionnaire respondents; only 9% of respondents claimed they first went to football alone and of their own volition.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe father was named as the key influence by half of respondents, and I sugges
defaultt that this reflects a more involved (and possibly more egalitarian) style of parenting in the late 20
defaultth
default and early 21
defaultst
default century, where fathers can spend leisure time with their daughters, not just their sons, through a shared regular football support.
